<div class="markdown"><div class="admonition is-question"><header class="admonition-header">Question:</header><div class="admonition-body"><p>How do we decide which optimizer is best for a given problem?</p></div></div></div>


<div class="markdown"><p>Questions to consider:</p><ul><li><p>How much do I know about my loss function?</p></li><li><p>Is my implementation of the loss function deterministic or stochastic?</p></li><li><p>Do I know that there a single global minimum or could there be multiple minima?</p></li><li><p>Do I really need to find the global minimum or is another minimum likely as good for my purposes?</p></li><li><p>Could there be saddle points?</p></li><li><p>Do I have a good initial guess of where the global minimum will be?</p></li><li><p>Can I place bounds on where the global minimum will be?</p></li><li><p>Are there non-trivial constraints that the minimum must satisfy?</p></li></ul><ul><li><p>Is the loss function smooth?</p></li><li><p>Do I know the length scale over which the function is smooth?</p></li><li><p>Can I compute the gradient of the loss function efficiently?</p></li><li><p>How many dimensions are the input parameters?</p></li></ul></div>


<div class="markdown"><h1>Rules of thumb:</h1><ul><li><p>If you have a function that's linear in all (or even a significant fraction of parameters), use that information to your advantage.</p></li><li><p>If you can make a good initial guess or provide bounds, use them.</p></li><li><p>If you can compute gradients of loss function eficiently, choose an algorithm that uses them.</p></li><li><p>For small dimensional problems <a href="https://julianlsolvers.github.io/Optim.jl/v0.9.3/algo/lbfgs/">BFGS</a> is a very common choice.</p></li><li><p>For high-dimensional problems, some version of gradient descent is a very common choice.  </p></li><li><p>There are many variants (e.g., stochastic, batched, add momentum), particularly if you don't need to find the true minimum.</p></li><li><p><a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1412.6980">ADAM</a> (or some variant on it) is a common choice.</p></li></ul></div>


<div class="markdown"><div class="admonition is-question"><header class="admonition-header">Question:</header><div class="admonition-body"><p>How does Julia create a python object / use python code inside julia?</p></div></div></div>


<div class="markdown"><ul><li><p>Most compiled languages built to be self-contained.  </p></li><li><p>Julia was designed to make cross-language development a little easier.</p></li><li><p>Built-in support for calling libraries written in C/C++/Fortran via <a href="https://docs.julialang.org/en/v1/base/c/">ccall</a></p></li><li><p><a href="https://github.com/JuliaPy/PyCall.jl">PyCall.jl</a>, <a href="https://github.com/JuliaPy/PythonCall.jl">PythonCall.jl</a>, and <a href="https://github.com/JuliaInterop/RCall.jl">RCall.jl</a> provide support for launching an  interpretted languages like Python and R, sending commands, and accessing results.</p></li><li><p>Built-in types (e.g., Integer, Float64, String) are usually implemented very similarly and can be accessed directly.</p></li><li><p>Compoud types (e.g., n-dimensional array, table, file handle) aren't standardized, so need either to be converted or extra code to allow direct access.</p></li><li><p>Trade-off between doing more behind-the-scenes automatically versus knowing precisely what your code is doing.</p></li></ul></div>

<div class="markdown"><ul><li><p>Create an accout with the archive you're querying.</p></li><li><p>Figure out how to authenticate via API.</p></li><li><p>Use <a href="https://astroquery.readthedocs.io/en/latest/gaia/gaia.html#asynchronous-query">Asynchronous queries</a></p></li><li><p>Call asynchronously, so your code doesn't block.</p></li></ul></div>

<div class="markdown"><div class="admonition is-question"><header class="admonition-header">Question:</header><div class="admonition-body"><p>When data is non linear and we know it is (e.g sinusoidal, exponential or quartic) then how do we formulate a predictive formula that we can derive our chi squared from?</p></div></div></div>


<div class="markdown"><p>For uncorrelated measurement noise:</p><p class="tex">$$\chi^2 = \sum_{i=1}^{N}  \left(\frac{y_i - f(x_i)}{\sigma_i}\right)^2$$</p></div>


<div class="markdown"><p>For non-diagonal covariance matrix:</p><p class="tex">$$\chi^2 = \sum_{i=1}^{N}  \left(y_i - f(x_i)\right)^{T} \Sigma^{-1} \left(y_i - f(x_i)\right)$$</p></div>
